    "synth_pr": "\n## Title: Fix missing error propagation in nas_timer implementation\n\n### Summary\nThe function `_nas_timer_db_insert_entry()` was ignoring the return value from `_nas_timer_db_insert()`, which indicates whether a timer became the first entry in the queue. This caused important timer state information to be lost, potentially leading to incorrect timer management behavior.\n\n### Changes\n- `openair3/NAS/COMMON/UTIL/nas_timer.c`: Modified `_nas_timer_db_insert_entry()` to return the restart status, updated function signature and documentation, and modified callers to capture the return value.\n\n### Reproduction\nUnder certain timing conditions, when a new timer is inserted and becomes the first in the queue, the system may not properly handle the timer precedence, potentially causing timers to expire out of order or with incorrect timing. This can be observed by monitoring timer expiration sequences in high-load scenarios where multiple timers are frequently added and removed.\n\nThe issue manifests as intermittent timing discrepancies in NAS procedures, particularly during connection establishment and mobility events where precise timer ordering is critical for protocol correctness.\n"
}